UNDIAGNOSED ILLNESS - INDIA (02): (KARNATAKA) FEBRILE, CHILDREN, SCRUB TYPHUS SUSPECTED, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
**********************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 14 Aug 2015
Source: Bangalore Mirror Bureau [edited]
http://www.bangaloremirror.com/bangalore/cover-story/Mystery-illness-hits-city-kids-parents-worried-docs-foxed/articleshow/48473219.cms


A growing number of children are worryingly being brought in to clinics and hospitals across the city with symptoms -- high fever and full-body rash -- of a mystery illness. The problem is that these symptoms are not associated with any single type of illness, foxing doctors and diagnosticians.

Paediatricians are unsure whether the illness is dengue fever, scrub typhus or just a run-of-the-mill viral infection. A few classify it as viral exanthema, which has been endemic in the city this season, and has become the most common reason for children missing school.

Dr Preeti Galagali, a senior paediatrician, says, "There have been many cases, and out of 30 to 40 cases every day, at least 10 children have presented with these symptoms. These symptoms could signal dengue, viral infections or scrub typhus. I have seen children who are as young as 4 months old present with these symptoms, and the toughest thing about this is prevention, as many times the fever may be transmitted from family members. The only advice we can give is to stay away from school and ask patients to build their immunity and to eat fruit. In many cases children lose their appetite and many also become nauseous; due to this their blood pressure dips and they may eventually develop hypotension and shock."

The biggest threat is, however, when parents come in late for an examination, as by that time the blood count has already deteriorated. If it is detected early, the condition can be managed through symptomatic treatment.

Dr Girish S V, consultant neonatologist, Cloudnine Hospital, says, "These rashes are seen in children in between the age of 15 months and 2 years. Another age group affected is school-going children. The rashes have been seen in almost 20 per cent of the paediatric population. The classic pattern of viral fever this season is that it peaks in 3 days and then subsides. It may recur and the rashes appear during the convalescence."

The rashes are seen usually in the ears, nose, hands, feet and buttocks. Dr Chetan Ginigeri Consultant Pediatric Intensivist, People Tree Hospitals, says, "We have seen cases that have 40 per cent similarity with scrub typhus. When we test them it may not be positive but on clinical examination it indicates all the symptoms. When we treat them for scrub typhus, they recover."

There are 2 types of tests that detect scrub typhus: One is the Weil-Felix test, which diagnoses rickettsial infections; another is the _Rickettesia_ IgM [antibody] test, which is not available in most laboratories here.

Dr Ginigeri says, "The Weil-Felix test is not the most accurate test, as it shows only 40-50 per cent positivity, even though it may be 100 per cent positive. Going by the numerous test results, we have seen 3 positive cases recently."

Symptoms: Fever; Rashes near nose, ears, etc after 3 days; Sore throat following the rashes.

Scrub Typhus is prevalent mostly in rural areas because of the proximity to mites. Dr Asha Benakappa, paediatrician at Vani Vilas Hospital, said, "This season we have seen a large number of cases of viral exanthematous fever, which is mainly classified as fever with rashes. Out of 525 cases of viral infection we have seen 5 positive [positive for what?] cases but have not seen any deaths."

What is a viral exanthema? This is an eruptive skin rash, which is associated with fever or other symptoms and is most common in children. It may [be] because of infectious pathogens, unhygienic environment and in a few cases allergy to medication. This season there has been an outbreak of the epidemic among children.

[Byline: Vandana Kamath]

