[The illness described in the news report above is compatible with a diagnosis of scrub typhus. However, the news report above fails to mention in the description of the clinical picture the presence of an eschar, a black lesion at the site of the chigger bite, that is often a useful diagnostic clue. More information on this outbreak from knowledgeable sources would be greatly appreciated.

Outbreaks of scrub typhus have previously been reported from South India (http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs12098-012-0721-0). Because scrub typhus can present in a non-specific manner, its diagnosis can be difficult and sensitive, and specific diagnostic tests may not be widely available.

Scrub typhus is caused by the rickettsia-like bacterium _Orientia tsutsugamushi_ that is transmitted by the bite of a chigger mite present in shrubberies. Symptoms develop 6 to 21 days after the chigger bite. Fever, headache, lymphadenopathy, and myalgias are common. A characteristic black eschar that is useful for making the diagnosis may be seen at the site of a chigger bite and a maculopapular rash may also be present. A picture of the eschar can be found at http://medind.nic.in/icb/t10/i8/icbt10i8p918.pdf.

Pneumonitis, meningoencephalitis, jaundice, renal failure, and myocarditis can develop if treatment is delayed. Because death rates for untreated scrub typhus patients are 1-30 per cent, treatment with doxycycline should begin immediately upon suspicion of scrub typhus without awaiting laboratory confirmation (http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/content/12/2/pdfs/v12-n2.pdf). Treatment with azithromycin has been found to be equally effective (http://aac.asm.org/content/51/9/3259.full, http://cid.oxfordjournals.org/content/39/9/1329.full, and http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3957884/).

The Weil-Felix test is an agglutination test based on the detection of antibodies to various _Proteus_ species, which contain antigens that cross-react with rickettsial antigens. The Weil-Felix test continues to be used for the diagnosis of scrub typhus in resource-poor regions, but it has poor sensitivity and specificity (http://www.japi.org/august2006/O-619.pdf). The gold standard for the diagnosis of scrub typhus has been the indirect fluorescent antibody (IFA) assay to detect _O. tsutsugamushi_-specific immunoglobulin M (IgM) and immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibodies, but the fluorescence microscopes that are required for performance of this assay are often not available in resource-poor settings where scrub typhus is endemic.

In one study of an outbreak of scrub typhus in South India (1), 67 children were diagnosed using an IgM enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA), which was said to be 91 percent sensitive and 100 percent specific. The children's ages ranged from 2 months to 11 years. Almost 60 percent resided in urban areas. Fever, edema of the face and extremities (due to a capillary leak syndrome), cough, vomiting, altered sensorium, anemia, low platelet count, and elevated liver enzymes were common. Almost 50 percent had an eschar at the site of the chigger bite. A rash (papular, petechial or erythematous) was seen on over 35 percent of patients; shock, in 45 percent; and respiratory failure, in 34 percent. Doxycycline was used for treatment in 46 children and azithromycin to 17 children. Of the 67 children, 8 children died with case fatality rate of 12 percent. Fatal cases were presented with refractory shock (100 percent), multiorgan failure (62 percent), acute renal failure (50 percent), acute respiratory failure (37 percent), or disseminated intravascular coagulopathy (12.5 percent).

1. Palanivel S, Nedunchelian K, Poovazhagi V, et al. Clinical Profile of Scrub Typhus in Children. Indian J Ped 2012;79(11):1459-1462.

Bangalore, with a population of about 8.42 million is the capital of the Indian state of Karnataka and is located in southern India inland on the Deccan Plateau, at a height of over 900 m (3000 ft) above sea level (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bangalore). Karnataka is located along the Arabian Sea to the west and the Indian states of Maharashtra to the north and Kerala to the south. A map of India showing the location of Karnataka and Bangalore can be seen at http://www.mapsofindia.com/images2/india-map.jpg. - Mod.ML]
